data.content:
MSTest has `CollectionAssert` and more specific asserts that give better error messages than `Assert.IsTrue`. Here's an improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)`** — on failure, shows `Expected: 3, Actual: 5` instead of just `Expected: True, Actual: False`
- **`Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count)`** — clearer intent than `IsTrue(count > 0)`
- **Add message strings** to `IsTrue` calls so failures are diagnosable
- **`users.Any(...)` over `Single(...)`** — avoids an `InvalidOperationException` blowing up the test with a confusing stack trace instead of a clean assertion failure

**Other useful tools:**

| Method | Use case |
|---|---|
| `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, item)` | Check membership |
| `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(collection)` | No duplicates |
| `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` | Same items, any order |
| `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` | Same items, same order |

For richer fluent assertions, consider **FluentAssertions** (`dotnet add package FluentAssertions`):

```csharp
users.Should().HaveCount(3)
     .And.OnlyContain(u => u.IsActive)
     .And.ContainSingle(u => u.Role == "Admin");
```
